Powerslide XC Skeleton II Nordic Inline Skates:

The 2015 Powerslied XC Skeleton is the ideal basic model for the nordic cross skater.

Simply step in with your shoes and off you go.

The snowboard type binding holds your foot in place as well as giving you perfect support.

The XC Skeleton is off road skating fun at itĀ´s best! ","
Technical Specification
The XC Skeleton II-shell provides a wide base which can be adjusted in length to fit various shoe sizes. You can use your own shoes to skate these nordic skates. ItĀ´s perfect for nordic skating schools or rental businesses. The quick release system helps you to adjust the size of your Nordic skates within a few seconds. Quick release systems are well known from the bike industry where it is used to fix the tires to the frame for example. This technology has been transferred to our nordic skates. The steel lever on our nordic skates is embedded in a shock absorber that has been added to the heel potion of the skate. The base is made out of a special composite compound that is super stiff thanks to the 15% fiberglass, which was mixed into the material. This makes the shell especially strong and supportive. It features a 165mm and 195mm long mounting distance with X-slot-system to be able to adjust all frames to the side, front and rear, in order to find the perfect skating position for everybody. The wide and strong flap is soft padded and locks the foot perfect in the shell. The anatomical strap at the front keeps the forefoot in perfect position and supports with high comfort.

column2:
>Powerdyne Bearing Press and Puller :

The Bearing Press & Puller Riedell for Roller Skate is made by PowerDyne
It will make it easy by using the bearing Press/Puller to install and replace your bearings in a cinch with the PowerDyne Bearing Press/Puller.  

Just follow the instructions below and you'll be back on the floor in no time!
To use the puller\, start with the handle up and the long pin down (sideways).
Then put the wheel on the outside\, push the handle down and it pulls the bearing out. Repeat to pull out the other bearing.

To use the press\, stand the pin up and put a bearing down on the pin.
Next\, put the wheel with the outside of the wheel (usually the printed side) facing up and put another bearing on the pin.
Tip the pin down (sideways) and carefully pull the handle down. You may have to guide the bearings a bit to get started.
The aluminum hub wheels may be a bit trickier than the nylon hub or no-hub wheels.
Do not use excessive force.
A very small amount of silicone oil around the outside of the bearing usually helps ease them into the aluminum hub wheels.

The Powerdyne Bearings press and puller come set up with an 8mm pin press and puller

column1: 23827,simple,Riedell3030AriaIceBoot,,Riedell 3030 Aria Competitive Ice Skate Boots,1,0,visible,The 3030 Arias is the most advanced strong and lightweight ice boot from Riedell.,"<span style=""font-family: Arial

column8: >The Riedell 3030 Aria is a sleek, strong, and lightweight boot, with the advantages of leather materials that mold to the skater’s foot, providing an exceptionally perfect fit.

column6: >Designed for top competitors, the <strong style=""line-height: inherit
column7: >Riedell Aria is for high-level skaters looking for ultimate performance and the best possible ergonomics and fit.

column6: >Inside the Aria, quadruple-layer reinforcements provide our firmest support and are heat moldable for the perfect fit. The extra firm support is balanced with the comfort of a luxuriously smooth antimicrobial leather lining that wicks moisture. Aria's taller toe box and an internal forefoot relief increase foot comfort on landings.

>Our innovative leather/cork heel and water-resistant ultra-thin outsole provide weight reduction, optimal support, and impact absorption. Aria's one-of-a-kind internal midsole technology further reduces weight and keeps you closer to the ice for added control.

>The winning balance of long-lasting comfort and support in the Aria skating boot is a choice for most demanding skaters, such as 2-time World Champion Stephane Lambiel and World Medalist Vincent Zhou.

33366,simple,RollLine7mmAxlelocknutsGold,,Roll-line 7 mm Axle Locknuts Gold,1,0,visible,"

Roll-Line 7mm Axle Locknuts Gold - Secure and Stylish

\nIntroducing the Roll-Line 7mm Axle Locknuts Gold, an essential accessory for your roller skates. These high-quality skate accessories come in a pack of 8 and feature a stylish gold (brass plated) finish. Designed to provide secure fastening and long-lasting durability, these locknuts are perfect for maintaining your skates and ensuring a smooth ride. Upgrade your skating gear with the best Roll-Line axle locknuts.","

Enhance Your Skating Experience with Roll-Line 7mm Axle Locknuts Gold

\nThe Roll-Line 7mm Axle Locknuts Gold are a crucial component for any skater looking to maintain their equipment at the highest level. These locknuts are designed to secure your axles firmly, ensuring safety and performance during your skating sessions. With a stylish gold (brass plated) finish, they not only offer functionality but also add a touch of elegance to your skates.

\nChoosing the Roll-Line 7mm Axle Locknuts means opting for premium quality and reliability. These locknuts are recommended to be changed after about six removals or if they can be turned with fingers, as worn-out nylon inserts may not stay securely in place. The Roll-Line company emphasizes the importance of maintaining your locknuts to ensure optimal performance and safety.

\nHistorically, roller skates used jam nuts instead of the nylon-inserted locknuts used today. Jam nuts had to be locked down completely to prevent loosening, requiring perfect alignment of spacers and bearings. Today, the use of nylon-inserted locknuts simplifies maintenance while ensuring secure fastening. The Roll-Line locknuts are designed to meet modern standards, providing a secure and reliable solution for your skating needs.

\n
  • High-Quality Construction: Made from durable materials with a brass-plated gold finish.

\n
  • Secure Fastening: Ensures your axles remain firmly in place during use.

\n
  • Easy Maintenance: Recommended to be replaced after about six removals or if they loosen easily.

\n
  • Pack Size: Comes in a pack of 8 for comprehensive maintenance.

\n
  • Compatibility: Suitable for various types of roller skates and skateboards.

\nUsing the Roll-Line 7mm Axle Locknuts Gold, you can ensure your skates are always in top condition. These locknuts provide a secure fit, reducing the risk of axle loosening and enhancing your overall skating experience. Regularly replacing your locknuts is essential for maintaining the performance and safety of your skates.

\nThe Roll-Line locknuts are designed with precision and quality in mind, making them a reliable choice for skaters who demand the best. Whether you're a professional skater or a recreational enthusiast, these locknuts will help you keep your skates performing at their best. Upgrade your skate maintenance routine with the best skate accessories from Roll-Line.",,,taxable,,1,,,0,0,0.15,,,,0,,,17.0,"Roller Skates > Roll Line Skates > Roll Line Accessories, Roller Skates > Roll Line Skates > Roll Line Skate Parts, Roller Skates > Roll Line Skates",,,http://rollerskateusa.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/7mm-Axle-Locknuts-GOLD.jpeg,,,,,RollLine7mmAxlelocknutsGold,,,,0,Roll Line,,,ExtraField 1,Roll-Line 7mm Axle locknuts Gold,1.0,0.0,ExtraField 6,"Roll Line Axle Locnuts 7mm GOLD

The Roll line company always recommends changing LockNuts after about 6 times of removal
or especially if you can turn them with your fingers.

When the NYLON insert wears out they will not stay in position unless locked completely down like the older style Jam Nuts.

If you look at the roller skating history years ago\, when we used Jam Nuts instead of the Nylon inserted Lock Nuts used today.
A Jam Nut must be locked down to keep from loosening and coming off.
To achieve good Roll from this type of configuration\, the sides of the spacer must be absolutely parallel\, without any burrs and just
a couple of thousandths of an inch wider than the web (that smaller center portion) of the wheel or space between the Bearings.
The sizes of the web of the Wheels vary between manufacturers and even between various wheels from the same manufacturer\, in some cases.

Many years ago\, the wheel manufacturers used to supply the Spacers with the Wheels.
When the Axle Nut is tightened down on the wheel (with bearings and a spacer)\, it creates a solid boss of material
(the inner race of the inside Bearing\, the Spacer\, and the inner race of the outside Bearing)
that effectively increases the Axle size from 7mm to approximately 14mm.
The increasing of the Axle size greatly reduces the possibility of bending or breaking any Axle.
By locking the Bearings and Spacer down\, it also assures that the center race of each Bearing is not spinning on the Axle\,
but that the balls of the Bearings are actually doing the work that they are intended to.
Tightening the Axle Nut on a Wheel without a Spacer can severely mis-align the center races of the bearings to the outer races
of the Bearings by compressing the inner races towards the center of the Wheel.
The Locked Down approach also requires near perfect alignment of the Wheel bore and the web of the Wheel must have very
clean square corners to provide a seat for the outer race of the Bearings.

Today\, Lock Nuts are accepted\, most Wheel manufacturers do not even supply the Wheel Spacers\, and the tolerances on the width
of the web of the Wheel are not held as tight as they once were.
To my knowledge\, Roll-Line is the only one still making Spacers for Wheels.
They normally come with a complete NEW Frame as an accessory.
Rollerskateusa.com does have spacers available in sets of 8 from Roll-Line.
(Just a Note: not every spacer will make every wheel work properly. Sometimes there are spacers that are non-parallel\,
have a burr\, or are just too small to match the web of a specific Wheel.)

The spacers have always been a part that the manufacturing cost must be minimized\, or for some manufacturers\, completely eliminated.
They are made from a long tube that is sawn into the Spacers\, and the tolerances are not usually as rigorously controlled as on other parts
of the Skate. To get the Spacers\, Bearings and Wheels to work\, means sometimes using multiple Spacers to get a specific wheel to roll properly.

When everything goes together well\, there should be little to no variation in the speed of a free spinning Wheel
(with the Axle Nut (Lock Nut) is just backed off) and when the Axle Nut (Lock Nut) is tightened down.

To achieve a Free Rolling complete set of Wheels in this manner will take time and patience and plenty of Spacers along with a good Bearing Press
like the our new Roll-Line Bearing Press/Puller.

Roll-Line 7mm Axle locknuts Gold,"
Features
The roll-line company always recommends changing LockNuts after about 6 times of removal
or especially if you can turn them with your fingers.
When the NYLON insert wears out they will not stay in position unless locked completely down like the older style Jam Nuts.
If you look at the roller skating history years ago, when we used Jam Nuts instead of the Nylon inserted Lock Nuts used today.
A Jam Nut must be locked down to keep from loosening and coming off.
To achieve good Roll from this type of configuration, the sides of the spacer must be absolutely parallel, without any burrs and just
a couple of thousandths of an inch wider than the web (that smaller center portion) of the wheel or space between the Bearings.
The sizes of the web of the Wheels vary between manufacturers and even between various wheels from the same manufacturer, in some cases.
Many years ago, the wheel manufacturers used to supply the Spacers with the Wheels.
When the Axle Nut is tightened down on the wheel (with bearings and a spacer), it creates a solid boss of material
(the inner race of the inside Bearing, the Spacer, and the inner race of the outside Bearing)
that effectively increases the Axle size from 7mm to approximately 14mm.
The increasing of the Axle size greatly reduces the possibility of bending or breaking any Axle.
By locking the Bearings and Spacer down, it also assures that the center race of each Bearing is not spinning on the Axle,
but that the balls of the Bearings are actually doing the work that they are intended to.
Tightening the Axle Nut on a Wheel without a Spacer can severely mis-align the center races of the bearings to the outer races
of the Bearings by compressing the inner races towards the center of the Wheel.
The Locked Down approach also requires near perfect alignment of the Wheel bore and the web of the Wheel must have very
clean square corners to provide a seat for the outer race of the Bearings.
Today, Lock Nuts are accepted, most Wheel manufacturers do not even supply the Wheel Spacers, and the tolerances on the width
of the web of the Wheel are not held as tight as they once were.
To my knowledge, Roll-Line is the only one still making Spacers for Wheels.
They normally come with a complete NEW Frame as an accessory.
Rollerskateusa.com does have spacers available in sets of 8 from Roll-Line.
<b>(Just a Note: not every spacer will make every wheel work properly. Sometimes there are spacers that are non-parallel,
have a burr, or are just too small to match the web of a specific Wheel.)
The spacers have always been a part that the manufacturing cost must be minimized, or for some manufacturers, completely eliminated.
They are made from a long tube that is sawn into the Spacers, and the tolerances are not usually as rigorously controlled as on other parts
of the Skate. To get the Spacers, Bearings and Wheels to work, means sometimes using multiple Spacers to get a specific wheel to roll properly.
When everything goes together well, there should be little to no variation in the speed of a free spinning Wheel
(with the Axle Nut (Lock Nut) is just backed off) and when the Axle Nut (Lock Nut) is tightened down.
To achieve a Free Rolling complete set of Wheels in this manner will take time and patience and plenty of Spacers along with a good Bearing Press
like the our new Roll-Line Bearing Press/Puller.
